hands_on_practices.problem:
Let $M$ be an oriented compact Riemannian manifold of dimension $n$ with smooth boundary $\partial M$, let $
u$ be the outward-pointing unit normal field along $\partial M$, and let $\omega \in \Omega^{k}(M)$ be a smooth $k$-form. Along $\partial M$, every differential form admits a normal-tangential decomposition: there is a unique decomposition
$$
\omega ig|_{\partial M} \;=\; \omega_{	op} \;+\; 
u^{ lat} \wedge \omega_{\perp},
$$
where $\omega_{	op} \in \Omega^{k}(\partial M)$ is tangential (it annihilates $
u$ under interior contraction) and $\omega_{\perp} \in \Omega^{k-1}(\partial M)$ is tangential. Here $
u^{ lat}$ denotes the metric dual $1$-form to $
u$, and $i_{
u}$ denotes interior product with $
u$. The Hodge star operator $\star$ is the isometry on forms induced by the metric and orientation, and the codifferential $\delta$ is defined on $k$-forms by $\delta = (-1)^{n(k+1)+1}\,\star\, d \,\star$. You may also use the standard identity $i_{X}(\star \alpha) = \star(\alpha \wedge X^{ lat})$ for any vector field $X$ and differential form $\alpha$.

A pair of natural boundary conditions arises in the analysis of the Hodge Laplacian on manifolds with boundary: the “absolute” boundary condition and the “relative” boundary condition for $k$-forms. One can show that these two are interchanged by the Hodge star operator $\star$.

Which of the following options correctly states the absolute boundary condition and the relative boundary condition for $k$-forms in terms of $i_{
u}$, $\delta$, $d$, and the tangential component $(\cdot)_{	op}$, and correctly explains their duality under $\star$? Select the best option.

A. Absolute: $i_{
u}\omega = 0$ and $i_{
u}(\delta \omega) = 0$. Relative: $\omega_{	op} = 0$ and $(d\omega)_{	op} = 0$. Moreover, $\omega$ satisfies the absolute condition if and only if $\star \omega$ satisfies the relative condition. This duality follows because $i_{
u}\omega=0$ if and only if $(\star \omega)_{	op}=0$ and $i_{
u}(\delta \omega)=0$ if and only if $(d\,\star \omega)_{	op}=0$, using $\delta = (-1)^{n(k+1)+1}\star d \star$ and $i_{
u}(\star  eta) = \star( eta \wedge 
u^{ lat})$.

B. Absolute: $i_{
u}\omega = 0$ and $i_{
u}(d \omega) = 0$. Relative: $\omega_{	op} = 0$ and $(\delta \omega)_{	op} = 0$. Moreover, $\omega$ satisfies the absolute condition if and only if $\star \omega$ satisfies the absolute condition. This is because $i_{
u}$ commutes with $\star$ on all $k$-forms.

C. Absolute: $\omega_{	op} = 0$ and $(d \omega)_{	op} = 0$. Relative: $i_{
u}\omega = 0$ and $i_{
u}(\delta \omega) = 0$. Moreover, $\omega$ satisfies the absolute condition if and only if $\star \omega$ satisfies the absolute condition, since $\delta = (-1)^{n(k+1)+1}\star d \star$ interchanges $d$ and $\delta$ without affecting boundary components.

D. Absolute: $i_{
u}\omega = 0$ and $i_{
u}(\delta \omega) = 0$. Relative: $\omega_{	op} = 0$ and $(d\omega)_{	op} = 0$. However, $\omega$ satisfies the absolute condition if and only if $\star \omega$ satisfies the relative condition only when $k$ is even; for odd $k$ the duality fails because $i_{
u}(\star  eta) = -\,\star( eta \wedge 
u^{ lat})$ introduces a sign that changes the tangential/normal decomposition.

E. Absolute: $i_{
u}\omega = 0$ only. Relative: $\omega_{	op} = 0$ only. The additional conditions involving $i_{
u}(\delta \omega)$ and $(d\omega)_{	op}$ are unnecessary because $\delta = (-1)^{n(k+1)+1}\star d \star$ implies them automatically for smooth forms.
